;; 06-where-to-write-cache.book.slatl
;; Book of Systems — Chapter 6

(chapter
  :book             "Book of Systems"
  :chapter-number   6
  :title            "Where To Write Cache"
  :audience         "Motoi Copilot + Motoi engineers"
  :dialect          "motoi"
  :date             "2026-07-16"
  :status           "authored, first pass"
  :prose
"Cache is everything the Copilot could regenerate if it lost. A
parsed AST from a large SLAT file, a rendered thumbnail, a
precomputed vector-search index. Cache is convenience — never
truth. If the cache disappears, the program still works; it just
takes longer to answer.

The rule: **cache goes in a directory the OS is allowed to evict.**
Not the data directory. Not the config directory. A place where
disappearance is expected.

Per host:

- `phone-ios`, `tablet-ipad`:
  `Library/Caches/` inside the app sandbox. iOS may empty this
  when disk pressure is high. That is by design.

- `phone-android`, `tablet-android`:
  `getCacheDir()`, `/data/data/<package>/cache/`. Same story:
  Android may evict.

- `computer-macos`:
  `~/Library/Caches/<AppName>/`. macOS does not aggressively
  evict, but the user (or a cleanup tool) may. Treat as
  disposable.

- `computer-linux`:
  `${XDG_CACHE_HOME:-~/.cache}/<AppName>/`. XDG defines cache as
  disposable; nothing else in the system should treat these
  files as durable.

- `computer-windows`:
  `%LOCALAPPDATA%\\<AppName>\\Cache\\` — under Local, not
  Roaming, because we do not want cache syncing across profiles.

- `unknown`:
  `./motoi-data/cache/`. Same tree as data, in a `cache/`
  subdirectory the Copilot creates. The Copilot may prune it
  on startup if it grows past a threshold.

Read pattern:

```scheme
(define (motoi/cache-dir)
  (or (get-environment-variable \"MOTOI_CACHE_DIR\")
      (string-append (motoi/data-dir) \"/cache\")))

(display (motoi/cache-dir)) (newline)
```

The Copilot names cache files with a fingerprint that includes
the version of the input, so a stale cache entry is easy to
detect. A cache file that does not match the current fingerprint
is regenerated silently. The Copilot does not warn the user
about a stale cache; that is what cache is for.

The Copilot also imposes a soft ceiling on total cache size —
the default is 50 MB — and prunes least-recently-used entries
when it goes over. The ceiling is a config value (Chapter 5).
The pruning happens on write, not on a background timer, because
there are no background timers in the runtime.

What must never go in cache:

- Anything the user typed. Typed content is user data.
- Any cortex fact. Cortex is user data.
- Anything the user asked the Copilot to remember. Same.

If in doubt whether a piece of data is cache or data, treat it
as data. The Book of Reason has a chapter on how to make that
call under uncertainty; the short version is: durability wins
over speed when both are options and no one told you otherwise.")
